        "content": "<p>I often find myself writing this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">foo</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">-- or `let x := foo`</span>\n<span class=\"k\">have</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hx</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">foo</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rfl</span><span class=\"bp\">;</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Is there a standard way to express this?</p>\n<p>My impression is that these redundant definitions help the proof automation tactics find things that they wouldn't  find when <code>x = foo : Prop</code> is buried inside <code>x : X := foo</code>.</p>",
